> You could make this recipe without stuffing the poblanos and it would still be delicious—the
> turkey, corn, rice, and cheddar filling is a splendid meal in its own right. But would it
> be just as fun? Probably not. Something about having all that goodness inside a warm
> pepper package makes it feel like you're piloting a raft down a river of flavor. (Kids
> and kids at heart who like to play pretend with their food—this one's for you.)

Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring @water{1%cup} and
@salt{pinch} to a boil in a #small pot{}. Once boiling, add @jasmine rice{1/2%cup} to
pot. Cover, lower heat, and reduce to a gentle simmer. Cook until tender, about
~{15%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until it's time for step 5.

Wash and dry all produce. Halve @poblano pepper{2} lengthwise, removing stems and seeds.
Place skin-side down on a #baking sheet{}. Roast in oven until blistered and softened,
about ~{15%minutes}. Once done, remove from oven and set aside to cool. Preheat broiler
to high.

Meanwhile, peel, halve, and finely chop @yellow onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Roughly
chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Drain half the @corn{7.5%ounce} from container (use the rest
as you like). Halve @lime{1}; cut one half into wedges. Heat a large drizzle of
@olive oil{2%tsp} in a #large tall-sided pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and
cook, tossing, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @ground turkey{10%ounce}, @dried oregano{1%tsp}, and @southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}
to pan with onion, breaking up meat into pieces. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.
Cook until lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add @chicken stock concentrate{1}, half the
@diced tomatoes{1/2%can}(drained), drained corn, and @water{1/4%cup} (use the rest of the
tomatoes as you like). Lower heat to medium and let simmer until thickened slightly,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Add cooked rice to pan with filling, stirring to combine, followed by half the
@cheddar cheese{1/2%cup}. Season with salt, pepper, and a squeeze or two of lime (to
taste). Fill poblano halves on baking sheet with as much filling as will fit (you'll
have some left over). Sprinkle remaining cheddar over top. Broil until cheddar is melted
and browned in spots, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Divide remaining filling between plates, then add 2 stuffed pepper halves to each plate.
Sprinkle cilantro over top and dollop with @sour cream{2%tbsp}. Serve with lime wedges on
the side for squeezing over.